<section id="pressarmor" class='fullbg bg-extra-pad bg-darker'>

	<div class="content-area container">
		
		<div class="row">
			<div class="col-md-6 pad4">
				<img class="img-responsive" src="https://pagely.c.presscdn.com/wp-content/themes/pagely14/img/press-armor.png" alt="PressARMOR - Secured WordPress" width="574" height="204" />
			</div>
			
			<article class="col-md-6">
		
				<h1 class="txt-color-white font-lg">We Are Secure</h1>
				
				<h3 class="subhead-bg txt-gray"><strong>Introducing Press<strong>ARMOR</strong>&trade;</strong></h3>
				
				
				
				<p class="lead">A comprehensive security architecture developed by Pagely® that hardens and protects our network, hardware, and applications. <strong>The primary focus is on prevention and the mitigation of risk to clients</strong>.</p>
				<p><button class="btn btn-sm btn-clear-light press_btn" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'Buttons', 'Clicked', 'Infra-PressArmor_LearnMore']);">Learn More <span class="caret"></span></button></p>
				
				<div class="morehidden txt-gray-light">
					<p><a href="/secure-wordpress-hosting/">Secure WordPress Hosting</a> is just how we do business. For base level security, we utilize the industry standard open-source web application firewall (WAF) <strong>mod_security</strong>, which means we block commonly known exploits by use of regular expressions and rule sets. Things like code injection attacks. In addition, we utilize custom <strong>rate limiting</strong> which means limiting the bandwidth to a particular category of traffic or connection type. This greatly reduces the chance of a DDoS attack succeeding.</p>

					<p>On top of the above, we also utilize <strong>chroot user separation</strong> and <span class="bg-accent-one padxsmall">real-time system malware scanning</span>. Scanning for malware means we’re constantly looking for things like trojan horses, viruses, worms, keyloggers, spyware, and adware. Chroot means we’re running certain processes inside of modified environments so they can’t access files outside their designated directory tree, and hence this is an additional hardening feature we’re using to keep the bad guys out.</p>
					
					<p>Additional rulesets at our <strong>network edge</strong> filter out much of the nefarious traffic long before it even has a chance to pass into our network.</p>
				</div>
			</article>
		</div>
	<div class="down-caret right">
	<i class="fa fa-caret-down txt-gray-dark"></i>
	</div>
	
	</div>
	
</section>


<section id="presscache" class='fullbg bg-extra-pad bg-light-gray'>

	<div class="content-area container">
		
		<div class="row">
			<div class="col-md-6 pad4">
				<img class="img-responsive" src="https://pagely.c.presscdn.com/wp-content/themes/pagely14/img/press-cache.png" alt="PressCACHE - Faster WordPress " width="574" height="204" />

			</div>

			<article class="col-md-6">
				<h1 class="txt-color-white font-lg">We are Fast</h1>
				
				<h3 class="subhead-bg txt-gray-dark"><strong>Introducing Press<strong>CACHE</strong>&trade;</strong></h3>
				
				
				
				<p class="lead">A global network of DNS routed cache nodes explicitly designed to serve WordPress page output. <strong>Your site, available instantly, from anywhere</strong>.</p>
				
				<p><button class="btn btn-sm btn-clear-light press_btn" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'Buttons', 'Clicked', 'Infra-PressCache_LearnMore']);">Learn More <span class="caret"></span></button></p>
				<div class="morehidden txt-gray-dark">
					<p>Press<strong>CACHE</strong>&trade; is a global WordPress acceleration system available for use by our clients. It works much like a CDN, but specifically designed to cache and serve WordPress page output.</p>
					<p>Essentially, a request for your website is routed to one of our global PoPs (Point of Presence) closest to the user. This shortens the distance between the user and your website thereby speeding up the load time of your site to a global audience. Press<strong>CACHE</strong>&trade; is available to all customers using our Press<strong>DNS</strong>&trade; nameservers.</p>
					
					<h4>Caching Locations</h4>
					<ul class="data-list list-unstyled nopad">
						<li><span class="bg-accent-one padxsmall">USA East</span> (Virginia) </li>
						<li><span class="bg-accent-one padxsmall">USA West</span> (N California)</li>
						<li><span class="bg-accent-one padxsmall">South America</span> (São Paulo)</li>
						<li><span class="bg-accent-one padxsmall">EU</span> (Ireland)</li>
						<li><span class="bg-accent-one padxsmall">Asia Pacific</span> (Singapore)</li>
						<li><span class="bg-accent-one padxsmall">Australia</span> (Sydney)</li>
					</ul>
					</div>
			
			</article>
			
			
		</div>
	<div class="down-caret right">
	<i class="fa fa-caret-down txt-gray"></i>
	</div>
	
	</div>

</section>

<section id="presscdn" class='fullbg bg-extra-pad bg-darker'>

	<div class="content-area container">
		
		<div class="row">
			<div class="col-md-6 text-center pad4">
				<img class="img-responsive" src="https://pagely.c.presscdn.com/wp-content/themes/pagely14/img/press-cdn.png" alt="PressCDN - WordPress CDN" width="574" height="204" />

			</div>

		
			<article class="col-md-6">
				
				<h1 class="txt-color-white font-lg">We are Faster still</h1>
				
				<h3 class="subhead-bg txt-gray"><strong>Introducing Press<strong>CDN</strong>&trade;</strong></h3>
				
								
				<p class="lead">Photos, images, and static assets served from a global network of servers. <strong>Faster download speeds for your site visitors</strong>.</p>
				
				<p><button class="btn btn-sm btn-clear-light press_btn" onclick="_gaq.push(['_trackEvent', 'Buttons', 'Clicked', 'Infra-PressCDN_LearnMore']);">Learn More <span class="caret"></span></button></p>

				<div class="morehidden txt-gray-light">
					
					<p>All of our plans come with our CDN built specifically for WordPress, Press<strong>CDN</strong>&trade;, which is powered by backend providers that include <span class="bg-accent-one padxsmall">MaxCDN</span>. That means your static assets are served according to the provider which has the closest location to your site’s particular visitor. For example, if your visitor happens to be accessing your site from Chennai India, your static assets may be served by Amazon Edge, since they have a location there. Having multiple providers on the backend means more efficiency and faster load times for your users.</p>
				
					<h4>Over 60 Caching locations available</h4>
					
				</div>
			
			</article>
		</div>
		
	</div>
</section>

